Stock Analysis and Prediction¶

Abstract¶

My target audience for this dataset would be :- Investors, Competitors, Stock brokers and financial advisors. I have analyzed the growth and performance of top 5 and worst 5 performing companies. I have also analysed Bank of America's stock performance from Feb 2013 to Feb 2018 on the basis of below mentioned points:

Finding any trend, pattern or seasonality in its stock including any anomaly that may have occurred. I have tried exploring both the internal (C-level executives hiring/firing etc.) and external factors (market factors like recession, governmental regulations etc.) that led to the impact on the stock performance. This would help the target audience to check how much potential a stock has and whether that stock is worth investing on.

Comparing Bank of America's stock performance with that of Wells Fargo and exploring the same internal/external factors. This helps the companies and their competitiors to design their future strategies and time their product/service reveal. Moreover, it helps investors in deciding whether they should withdraw their shares from one company and invest in the other one instead.

Apart from that, I have applied a time series forecasting model i.e Facebook Prophet to predict the future performance of both the banks stocks on the basis of historical performance and other factors. This helps the financial advisors who can advise their customers on where they should invest their money.

In [13]:
def plotGraph(data, namesList, titleList):
    for i in range(len(titleList)):
        matchedDataIdx = updatedData['Name'].isin(namesList[i])
        sub = updatedData[matchedDataIdx].groupby(['Name', 'date'])['Growth'].sum().reset_index()
        plt.figure(figsize(20, 10))
        sns.pointplot(x = 'date', y = 'Growth', hue = 'Name', data = sub, scale = 0.5)
        plt.title(titleList[i]  , size = 25)
        plt.legend(markerscale = 2, prop = {'size' : 15})
        plt.xlabel('Time', size = 20)
        plt.ylabel('Growth', size = 20)
        # We do not need any ticks on the x-axis
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.show()

NVIDIA stock prices increased by almost 18 times as can be seen from the growth analysis. It's stocks showed a sharp rise in end of 2016 and 2017 because of it's presence in Gaming, Artificial Intelligence, Virtual Reality and NVDA's capability of building hardware for self-driving cars. Every single one of these areas is attractive to an investor who wants exposure to emerging technologies and moreover the scope of these areas in heavily growing. One more factor that led to rise in NVDA's stock prices is that the demand for pascal GPU's grew heavily in 2016 and the graphic cards were in short supply. Also, demand for their data centre's grew very much.

On the other hand, the worst performing stocks of Chesapeake Energy Corporation has been involved in a lot of controversies and lawsuits and that's why it's share prices dropped that much.

# Correlation plot
def get_correlation(cor, upper = 0.99, lower = -0.99, blank = False):
    corr = {}
    for i in cor:
        obj = cor[i][cor[i].apply(abs).argsort()[::-1]]
        obj = obj[(obj > upper) | (obj < lower)]
        obj = obj[obj.index != i]
        if len(obj) == 0:
            if blank: corr[i] = None
        else:
            corr[i] = {}
            for j in obj.index:
                corr[i][j] = cor[i].loc[j]
    return corr

Bank of America: When the new administration came post-elections in Jan 2017, they provided a pro-growth platform and promised to implement business friendly measures. For banks, this could eliminate some of the most onerous regulations of the 2010 Dodd-Frank Act and hence it could help in freeing banks up to increase lending and return more capital to shareholders. Moreover, the Federal Reserve consolidated the post-election gains in bank stocks by raising the fed funds rate, which is the key short-term interest rate benchmark in the United States. These factors combined with the recent rally in long-term interest rates, started adding additional revenue and profits each quarter for Bank of America.

Apart from that, bofa earned a profit of 7.3 billion dollars for the fourth quarter of 2018, which exceeded the expectations of all the investors and analysts. Marrill Edge (investment arm of bofa) brokerage assets grew by 5% i.e. 25b$ of net assests flowed into their accounts which indicated the excellent growth rate.

Wells Fargo: On the other hand, Wells Fargo was found associated with Account Fraud Scandal in late 2016, where they created millions of fraudulent savings and checking accounts on behalf of Wells Fargo clients without their consent. They also fired the whistleblower and many employees to generate fake accounts in 2017 and hence both customers and investors lost confidence and Wells Fargo stocks saw a lot of volatility.

# Moving Averages (10, 50 and 200)
bofaData['10_d_avg'] = bofaData.close.rolling(window=10).mean()
bofaData['50_d_avg'] = bofaData.close.rolling(window=50).mean()
bofaData['200_d_avg'] = bofaData.close.rolling(window=200).mean()
updatedBofaData = bofaData.set_index('date')

fig = tls.make_subplots(rows=2, cols=1, shared_xaxes=True)

for col in ['close']:

Moving Average is beneficial to analyze the stock performance in the longer time span because it smoothes out the fluctuations and volitility of the shorter intervals. And here therfore, 200 day moving average smmothes out a lot of spkies whereas a 10 day MA quite closely represents the actual closing price.

So we can see that the above analysis will be helpful to investors and shareholders who wish to see the stock prediction of the company and decide whether the stock is worth investing or not.
